body:
Hi @HeinRique ,

Thanks for the detailed description. 

From the error stack I can see that the problem occurs after we have fit the model and are trying to get the evaluation metrics. The code is trying to get classification metrics, but it looks like your target is a number rather than the discrete classes required for classification. So I suspect the problem is that you are using a classification estimator when you should be using a regression estimator.

I also see that your target field is set as a string in the feature definitions but is actually a float. Using one hot encoding on this field will split it into multiple columns; one for each unique value, which is probably a mistake. Just leave the target as an int or float with the feature strategy as none, and frame your model as a regression problem. If you want to do classification you would convert this continuous variable into a discrete one, for example by bucketing the numeric values into fixed classes in Qlik.

The n_features input you are sending looks ok. The SSE breaks the input into multiple columns on the `|` delimiter and then converts data types based on the feature definitions you send to the model. The feature strategies such as scaling and one hot encoding are then applied which may result in a different number of columns than the input. You can see the transformations the data goes through by passing `debug=true` in the `ExecutionArgs`.

Hi @HeinRique ,

This new error would be coming from the Skater package. There's an additional description along with the error that should give the possible reasons:
1. 0 or infinite divisions
2. perturbed values == original values
3. feature is a constant 

The importances are calculated by changing the value of features and checking how the model behaves compared to the original values. Could there be a reason this is not possible for a particular feature in your dataset? You can turn on debugging and look at the input dataframe before we fit the model. The most obvious issue would be a constant value across all samples.

If you don't really need the feature importances, you could turn them off by passing `calculate_importances=false` argument in the `ExecutionArgs`.

@HeinRique , no need to apologize, this is what the issues section is for!

It looks like there is a bug in the code when returning a numerical prediction. The quick fix is to update the following code block in the _utils.py file from rows 73 to 74. You'll need to update the file under `qlik-py-tools\qlik-py-env\core`.

```
            # Convert values to type SSE.Dual according to the template list
            if template[0] == "str":
                this_row.append(SSE.Dual(strData=row))
```

Replace with:

```
            # Convert values to type SSE.Dual according to the template list
            if template[0] == "str":
                if type(row) is not str:
                    row = "{0:.5f}".format(row)
                this_row.append(SSE.Dual(strData=row))
```

I'll try to get a proper fix and release in soon.

After some testing I realised that I missed a limitation of SSE functions; they can only have one return type. So the changes I made yesterday to return a numeric or string prediction depending on the target doesn't quite work for chart expressions. It does work when getting predictions in the load script.

I've just gone back to the simpler approach of returning the prediction as a string in all cases and letting Qlik convert it to a dual automatically. Can you grab the latest `__main.py__` and `_sklearn.py` files and replace them in your `qlik-py-tools\qlik-py-env\core` directory once more? You don't need to get the whole repository again.

https://github.com/nabeel-oz/qlik-py-tools/tree/master/core

Here's an app with your data that I used for testing: 
[_Git Issue 31.zip](https://github.com/nabeel-oz/qlik-py-tools/files/3283934/_Git.Issue.31.zip)

On my app test, both of them works just fine. So I tried to:

- **Copy my chart to your app**: the dimension one stop working.
- **Check the load script**: the "Feature Expression" tab was identical.
